For me, the phrase depicts the state of socio-technical system design in all itâ€™s glory, which is to say, it lays bear the truth of the meagre progress. And yet, this is what we do repeatedly as engineers and designers. We reach too quickly for the seemingly simpler solution, without doing the difficult and often fruitless work of digging deeper behind our tech interventions and looking at the sociological dimension. Too much traffic? More roads. Too much carbon emission? Everything is a socio-technical systems.

The Wire in the age of Extremely Online

For all itâ€™s acclaim and praise as a sociological masterpiece, in the age of Extremely Online, I canâ€™t help but wonder if David Simonâ€™s ability to reach beyond the simply apparent and reveal the deeper society behind the mundane details of life, failed him on one deliciously curious front: the so called surveillance capitalism of our modern world.

In a world where our internet is dominated by a few massive tech giants, and where the phrase â€œsurveillance capitalismâ€ has gained some popularity, I wonder if The Wire missed a trick by not exploring the nefarious capability inherent in the wire tap infrastructure used in the show (and after which the show is ostensibly named).

I, for one, would have loved to see the genius of Simon brought to bear on a story arc where a Senator leaned on the police department to spy on a Church Pastor and his congregation, as a prelude to the mountains of data Facebook collects today.

Ah well. Perfection is the enemy of progress. Or no?

End Note 1: Thickness in Design?

There is a book about The Wire ( The Wire:Truth Be Told), and the introduction is written by David Simon himself. Itâ€™s a perfectly consistent (and riveting piece) by David, which starts like this: â€œSwear to God, it was never a cop show.â€

In my view, Simonâ€™s introduction essay supports a view of one Tom Brookes on the LSE Blog, where he writes about The Wire as sociology. It was in this description that I first learned about the concept of â€œthick descriptionâ€, and also about the work of Clifford Geertz. Iâ€™m still reading and trying to comprehend his 1975 essay entitled â€œThick Description: Towards ad Interpretive Theory of Cultureâ€ but Geertzâ€™s work and the point Brookes makes have both helped me to understand why Iâ€™m a fan of the The Wire. The attention to detail, the inclusion of small, seemingly inconsequential details and artifacts, pays homage to the true complexity of the context in which The Wire is set, and in doing so paints a richer picture.

Simonâ€™s essay talks, implicitly at least, about the detail included in the show. â€œWe staged The Wire in a real city, with real problemsâ€ he writes, and then â€œthose foreign to Baltimore will miss many a reference, but not, I believe, the overall sense that they are learning about a city that matters.â€ All of this emphasizes the point that Brooke made: that there is rich visual thickness in The Wire, that helps to characterize this as a real sociological work.
